        <body>
            <head><name type="stone">CIIC 11. <placeName type="townland"
                >Drummin</placeName></name> I, Co. <placeName
                    type="county">Roscommon</placeName></head>
            <ab><rs>National Monuments Service Record Number: <ref
                target="http://webgis.archaeology.ie/HistoricEnvironment/?SMRS=RO015-051001-"
                >RO015-051001-</ref>
                </rs></ab>
            <div type="description" n="site type">
                <head>Site Type</head>
                <p>Ringfort/rath</p>
            </div>
            <div type="description">
                <head>Description</head>
                <div type="description" n="site">
                    <head>Site</head>
                    <p><q>On a gentle SW-facing slope. Circular grass-covered area with mature deciduous trees (diam. 55m E-W; 54m N-S) 
                        defined by an earthen bank ... [Two] standing stones (RO015-051001-; RO015-051003-) are inside the perimeter at 
                        SW, the first with an ogham inscription. In 1985 a second ogham stone (RO015-051004-) was discovered in the bank 
                        that became dislodged and is now lying on top of the bank at SW</q> 
                        (<ref
                            target="http://webgis.archaeology.ie/HistoricEnvironment/?SMRS=RO015-051002-"
                            >NMS Survey database</ref>). </p>
                </div>
                <div type="description" n="monument">
                    <head>Monument</head>
                    <p><rs type="material"/>Sandstone (SMR file),
                        <rs type="dimensions">
                            <measure unit="metre" type="length" rend="height">1.09</measure>m x
                            <measure unit="metre" type="length" rend="width">0.41</measure>m x
                            <measure unit="metre" type="length" rend="depth">0.51</measure>m
                            (converted from <ref type="bibliog" target="#MAC1945"
                                ><bibl><author>Macalister</author>
                                    <date when="1945">1945</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                        >16</biblScope></bibl></ref>). </rs>
                    </p>
                   
                </div>
                <div type="description" n="text">
                    <head>Text</head>
                    <p><q>The V is faint and there is a fracture at the end of the inscription, but it seems to be complete</q> (<ref type="bibliog" target="#MAC1945"
                        ><bibl><author>Macalister</author>
                            <date when="1945">1945</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                >16</biblScope></bibl></ref>).  <ref
                                    target="http://titus.fkidg1.uni-frankfurt.de/database/ogam/ogquery.asp?ciic1=011"
                                    >Gippert</ref> remarks that <q>by 1996, the angle seems to have suffered more levelling so that the B-strokes of 
                                    the N have become even harder to trace. Of Macalister's reading, neither the medial O nor his V could be ascertained</q>
                      </p>                             
                               
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="edition" xml:lang="ga">
                <head xml:lang="en">Transliteration</head>
                <ab>
                    <persName><w lemma="CUNOVATOS">CU<unclear reason="damage">N</unclear><supplied reason="lost">OV</supplied>ATO</w></persName>                    
                   </ab>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                <head>Translation</head>
                <ab></ab>
            </div>
            <div type="figure">
                <head>Images</head>
                <div type="figure" n="three-dimensional-model">
                    <head>3D model</head>
                </div>
                <div type="figure" n="photographs">
                    <head>Photographs</head>
                    <p><ref
                        target="http://titus.fkidg1.uni-frankfurt.de/ogam/l/011/011x011l.jpg"
                        >Photo from <ref type="bibliog" target="#MAC1914"
                            ><bibl><author>Macalister</author>
                                (<date when="1914">1914</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                    >Pl. XV</biblScope></bibl></ref>)</ref> </p>
                </div>
                <div type="figure" n="drawings">
                    <head>Drawings</head>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <head>Commentary</head>
                <list type="witDetail">
                    <item n="1"><p>This is one of the inscriptions listed by <ref type="bibliog"
                        target="#MCM1991"><bibl><author>McManus</author> (<date when="1945"
                            >1991</date>, <biblScope type="pp">94-5</biblScope></bibl>)</ref> in
                        which apocope (loss of final consonants or syllables) begins to show
                        itself (CUNOVATO (earlier -os). <q>The final S has been dropped but lowering has not taken place in the first syllable</q>. 
                        On this basis it may be dated to the 
                        <origDate notBefore="0500" notAfter="0550">first half of the sixth century</origDate> 
                        <ref type="bibliog"
                            target="#MCM1991">(<bibl><author>McManus</author> <date when="1945"
                                >1991</date>, <biblScope type="pp">97, 176 note 40</biblScope></bibl>)</ref>. However, 
                        although <ref type="bibliog" target="#MAC1945"
                            ><bibl><author>Macalister</author> 
                                (<date when="1945">1945</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                    >16</biblScope></bibl></ref>) notes that the 
                        inscription <q>seems to be complete</q>, an original CUNOVATOS is possible considering that the end of the stone is fractured. 
                        This would make the estimated date even earlier.</p>
                       </item>
                                   </list>
            </div>
            <div type="history" n="locations">
                <head>Locations</head>
                <div type="history" n="locations">
                    <head>Found</head>
                    <p>
                        <rs type="found">Discovered in the rath/ringfort sometime before 1914 (first mention) in the townland of
                                <placeName type="townland">Drummin</placeName> and barony of
                            <placeName type="barony">Castlereagh</placeName>. (GPS coordinates
                            <geo> -8.369881, 53.834383</geo>)</rs>
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div type="history" n="locations">
                    <head>Original</head>
                    <p>
                        <rs type="origLocation">Unknown</rs>
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div type="history" n="locations">
                    <head>Last Recorded</head>
                    <p>
                        <rs type="lastLocation">Still standing in the rath/ringfort <ref
                            target="http://webgis.archaeology.ie/HistoricEnvironment/?SMRS=RO015-051001-"
                                >National Monuments Service Historic Environment viewer on
                                www.archaeology.ie</ref>. </rs>
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="history" n="record">
                <head>History of Recording</head>
                <p>According to <ref type="bibliog" target="#MAC1914"
                    ><bibl><author>Macalister</author> 
                        (<date when="1914">1914</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                            >139</biblScope></bibl></ref>), <q>found by one Mr. Igoe, of the Ordnance Survey, and by him communicated to Dr. Douglas Hyde</q></p>
            </div>
